snippet.textDisplay:
Nice and fun video about a very important subject, but you miss a major point right at the beginning.
What they grow from is not a seed but actually a gymnosperm, an embryonic plant that does not require the time or conditions for sprouting; this is why they can start growing in just a few days, right on top of bare ground and with hardly any moisture. I live in an area that they grow and although they do not get huge like in the video they are still a terrible nuisance, and as the video says, they are very difficult to gather and dispose of. Finally, the origin I had always read was the Ukrainian farmers accidentally brought it with them in their hemp seed. Much like thistles are not an invasive species in Scotland, but obviously are here, these plants are likely not so virulent where they came from, either.
Fun fact, the green parts of the plant are edible when they are just a couple inches tall, at this point they are easily mistaken for a small clump of grass. Only upon close inspection can you see that they are not blades but actually stem like.

I live in an area that they grow and although they do not get huge like in the video they are still a terrible nuisance, and as the video says, they are very difficult to gather and dispose of. snippet.textDisplay: One of my tasks during my first summer job was to clean up a transformer substation that was full halfway up the fence with tumbleweeds. Until I watched your video I never thought about how dangerous the situation was. 27000 volts on the low side, more than 100000 on the high side, 3 feet of tinder waiting for a gust of wind to bring in one last unlucky tumbleweed, and two blissfully ignorant summer students working below. We cheated death and didn't even know it. Eeek!
